Self-organizing map analysis of watershed conditions at Hungerford Brook

Dustin Kincaid

11/11/2021

Objective

Cluster high-flow event characteristics and antecedent watershed conditions to evaluate how these factors converge as flux regimes (clusters) to produce variability in event N and P yields


Select variables to keep

Per K Underwood: if two variables are strongly correlated (negatively or positively) they can effectively double-weight a particular factor important in driving clustering; thus, keep just one of the variables to serve as a proxy for that factor

Decisions for eliminating variables w/ correlations >70%
  • These decisions were tough to make and need review
    • rain_event_total_mm and API_4d are highly correlated (87.2%), but represent different things, so Im going to leave both for now
    • airT_4d and VWC_pre_wet_30cm are highly correlated (88%); leaving both for now
    • rain_int_mmPERmin_max + airT_4d are correlated (76.2%); leaving both for now
    • VWC_pre_wet_30cm + time_sinceLastEvent are correlated (-72%); leaving both for now
    • Im removing pre-event stream concentrations, because they keep driving the separation of a singular event that doesnt make sense
  • I feel OK about these decisions, but they should be reviewed as well
  • If the 1-d and 4-d values for a variable are highly correlated, use the 4-d value for weather vars and 1-d values for measures of catchment wetness
  • Trying to find a VWC variable that correlates well with GW level so that I can remove GW level vars (no GW data in 2017)
    • gw_1d_allWells and VWC_pre_wet_30cm most highly correlated (96.3%); same with VWC_pre_wet_15cm (94.1%), except slightly less linear at higher values
    • drop gw_4d_allWells and use VWC as a proxy for GW level
    • drop VWC_pre_wet_45cm & wet transect equivalent (well use soil vars measured at 15cm)
    • VWC_pre_wet_15cm and VWC_pre_wet_30cm highly correlated (90.5%); VWC_pre_wet_30cm is better correlated with GW level, so going to keep VWC_pre_wet_30cm even though Im keeping all 15cm values for other soil vars
    • gw_1d_allWells and gw_4d_allWells are highly correlated (99.5%); remove gw_4d_allWells
  • Soil variables
    • SoilTemp_pre_dry_15cm & equivalent at wet transect are highly correlated (99.4%); lets keep wet transect temps
    • VWC_pre_dry_15cm & VWC_pre_wet_15cm are highly correlated (85.9%); keep wet version b/c keeping most wet vs.pre versions
  • MET variables
    • airT_4d and dewPoint_4d are highly correlated (97.8%), as is dewPoint_1d (95.6%); removing both dewPoints
    • airT_4d and SoilTemp_pre_wet_15cm are highly correlated (95.4%); drop SoilTemp_pre_wet_15cm, I previously dropped airT_4d b/c still had diff_airT_soilT, but that var didnt differentiate clusters
    • rain_int_mmPERmin_max + rain_int_mmPERmin_mean arent super correlated, but represent similar things, so removing the mean version
  • Stream variables
    • q_event_delta & q_event_max are highly correlated (94%); lets keep q_event_max
    • q_event_max + q_mm are highly correlated (86.2%); lets keep q_event_max b/c NO3 & SRP yields calculated using q_mm
  • I removed these variables after the initial SOM run b/c they did not differentiate clusters
    • diff_airT_soil_T; PET_mmHR; Redox_pre_dry_15cm
Look at correlations again after dropping variables



Decisions for eliminating remaining tricky variables by looking at PCA
  • Variables are not transformed to improve normality
  • Using Pearson correlation vs.covariance matrix given the untransformed data where vars have different units and ranges
myData <- hford_drop %>% 
  # Keep only complete observations/rows (no NAs in any of the columns)
  na.omit()

# scale = TRUE = correlation matrix; scale = FALSE = covariance matrix
  PCA <- prcomp(myData, scale = TRUE, center = TRUE)
  factoextra::fviz_pca_var(PCA, repel = TRUE)



Self-organizing map (SOM)

Prepare data & set up grid/lattice dimensions

Were only using complete observations/rows (no NAs in any columns)
According to the heuristic rule from Vesanto 2000, number of grid elements/grid size/nodes = 5 * sqrt(n)
To determine the the shape of the grid (ratio of columns to rows), we use the ratio of the first two eigen values of the input data set as recommended by Park et al.2006

## [1] No. of complete observations: 89 out of 105 observations
## [1] No. of Vesanto nodes: 47
## [1] Ratio of columns to rows: 1.5



Run SOM for a suite of grid/lattice configurations, # of nodes, and # of clusters

Code courtesy of Kristen Underwood (hidden)

## [1] Weighting method used: noPCA

Choose the best SOM run based on non-parametric F-stat and quantization error

We want to maximize npF (ratio of b/w cluster variance) and minimize QE (mean distance b/w each data vector & best-matching unit)
